<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Thomas More</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Wed Nov 15, 2023</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<!--pdf exclude begin-->

<p class="smaller">
[<em>Editor&rsquo;s Note: The following new entry by Gerard Wegemer
replaces the
 <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/fall2023/entries/thomas-more/">former entry</a>
 on this topic by the previous author.</em>]</p>

<!--pdf exclude end-->

<p>
Thomas More (1478&ndash;1535), as the young &ldquo;man for all
seasons&rdquo; first so called by Erasmus (9 June 1510 letter to More
[<em>EW</em> 271.27] and c. September 1521 letter to Guillaume
Bud&eacute; [<em>EW</em> 1376.9]), has been recognized as one of the
foremost early modern humanists in England, particularly in view of
his well-known <em>Utopia</em> and his <em>History of King Richard
III.</em> Whether years later Chancellor More remained such a man, or
became repressive in his outlook and action, remains a topic of
controversy. After law school and the best education available in
London and Oxford, More mastered ancient Greek and encouraged Erasmus
to do so as well, convinced of the need to return to the sources of
classical and biblical thought. Throughout his life he stressed the
importance of philosophy; he himself devoted his early morning hours
to study and reflection even during his busiest years&mdash;as is
evidenced by the twenty books, the 291 poems, and the surviving 151
letters that he wrote in the midst of an active civic life. He
identified himself frequently as a &ldquo;citizen of London&rdquo; and
was known as a distinguished lawyer, judge, member of Parliament,
ambassador, and prominent proponent of women&rsquo;s education; he
became Speaker of the House of Commons, Chancellor of the Duchy of
Lancaster, then for three years Lord Chancellor of England and
prosecutor of heretics under King Henry VIII. In taking the oath of
office as Chancellor, More swore to uphold England&rsquo;s
128-year-old heresy laws and, while he was in office, six individuals
were convicted of heresy by ecclesiastical courts and then executed
under secular law. He himself was executed for failing to recognize
the legislation of 1532&ndash;34 making Henry VIII head of the Church
of England and for failing to support the king&rsquo;s divorce from
Catherine of Aragon and marriage to Anne Boleyn.</p>

<p>
This entry is limited to Thomas More&rsquo;s understanding and
practice of philosophy, enlightened, as he believed it to be, by
biblical revelation. Intellectually, he was most deeply indebted to
Plato, Aristotle, Cicero, Seneca, the Bible, and the Latin and Greek
Church Fathers (especially Augustine, Jerome, Basil, and Chrysostom;
see <em>Concordances</em> in
 <a href="#Oth">Other Internet Resources</a>).</p>
 </div> 

<div id="toc"><!--Entry Contents-->
<ul>
